{
  "text": "[28] [CITATION_1] suggested that a 2 km thick subsurface permafrost layer above a 50 km 3 magma chamber would melt in a few tens of thousands of years. This is of the same order as the time taken for discharge to peak in our own models, indicating that ice could significantly reduce total discharge. We thus ran the baseline model with a 1 km thick layer of subsurface ice (Figure 8 ), modeled after [CITATION_2] , who approximated the melting process as a cooling period over a small finite temperature interval ÁT. During melting the material is assigned an augmented specific heat given by",
  "correct_citation": {
